  "insights": [
    {
      "title": "OAuth2 dominates auth",
      "detail": "62 of 100 apps expose OAuth2 as a primary auth method, with API keys the main fallback (60). Basic auth is rare (5). This means managed OAuth is the highest-leverage capability for a toolkit platform."
    },
    {
      "title": "Most apps are self-serve",
      "detail": "76 of 100 apps let a developer get credentials themselves (free or trial); 24 are gated behind a paid plan, admin approval, or contact-sales. The gated cluster is concentrated in enterprise/fintech categories."
    },
    {
      "title": "Buildability is high but rarely zero-effort",
      "detail": "76 buildable today, 17 partial (need a connector but the API exists), 7 blocked. The most common blocker is \"Partner / contact-sales gate\"."
    },
    {
      "title": "Composio already covers the bulk of demand",
      "detail": "48 of 100 apps already have a Composio toolkit with genuine tool/trigger counts. The long tail (open-source CLI tools, niche fintech, media-native AI apps) is where new build work lives."
    },
    {
      "title": "Easy wins vs outreach",
      "detail": "74 apps are immediate easy wins (self-serve + buildable). 24 need partnership/outreach or have a real blocker. Prioritize the former for fast toolkit parity."
    }
  ]
}